If you're using a loop to add event listeners to a list of stars, the issue might be due to the scope of the variable `index` inside the loop. In JavaScript, variables are scoped to the block they are declared in. 

Here's an example of how you might be adding event listeners in a loop:

```javascript
for (let index = 0; index < stars.length; index++) {
  stars[index].addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log(index); // This will always print the last index
  });
}
```

In this case, the `index` variable is being used inside an arrow function, which has its own scope. When the event listener is called, `index` is not the current index of the star, but the last index of the loop.

To fix this issue, you can use a closure to capture the current value of `index` inside the loop:

```javascript
for (let index = 0; index < stars.length; index++) {
  (function(i) {
    stars[i].addEventListener('click', () => {
      console.log(i);
    });
  })(index);

